import java.sql.*; // For all Java DB related classes, interfaces etc.. they can be imported as per the requirement of your project and according to JDBC API documentation.
// It's generally best practice not importing them directly but use their fully qualified name in code like this:  javax.sql.*; for example if you are using MySQL database then it should look something similar to below...   java.sql.*; or the ones from other databases such as Oracle, Postgres etc..
// Import all necessary packages once and reuse them whenever needed instead of repeating imports each time we need a class/method in our code which is not possible with standard Java libraries only due JDBC API usage  .   So this approach will help to reduce the repetitive coding effort.    And also remember that using raw SQL would be considered as injection attack point, so it'll add an extra layer of security here for sure!